00":"1200","1244":"1244","1222":"1222","1297":"1297","1220":"1220","Abt 1215":"circa 1215","1285":"1285","1196":"1196","1250":"1250","Abt 1219":"circa 1219","abt 1244":"circa 1244","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Midelton, Yorks, England":"Yorkshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Middleton, West Riding Yorkshire, England":"Middleton, Yorkshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Stockeld, Yorkshire, England":"Stockeld, Yorkshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"Abt 1215–":"about 1215–Deceased","1215–Male":"1215–Deceased","1222–Female":"1222–Deceased","1220–Female":"1220–Deceased","1244–1285":"1244–1285","1250–1297":"1250–1297","1250–Male":"1250–Deceased","1196–Male":"1196–Deceased","1200–Female":"1200–Deceased","1215":"1215","1200":"1200","1244":"1244","1222":"1222","1297":"1297","1220":"1220","Abt 1215":"about 1215","1285":"1285","1196":"1196","1250":"1250","Abt 1219":"about 1219","abt 1244":"about 1244","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","Midelton, Yorks, England":"Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","Middleton, West Riding Yorkshire, England":"Middleton, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","Stockeld, Yorkshire, England":"Stockeld, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Middelton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of the places so called. In over thirty instances from many different areas, the name is from Old English <i>midel</i> ‘middle’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘enclosure, settlement’. However, Middleton on the Hill near Leominster in Herefordshire appears in Domesday Book as <i>Miceltune</i>, the first element clearly being Old English <i>micel</i> ‘large’, ‘great’ (see   Middlebrook  ). Middleton Baggot and Middleton Priors in Shropshire have early spellings that suggest <i>gem̄thhyll</i> (from <i>gem̄th</i> ‘confluence’ + <i>hyll</i> ‘hill’) + <i>tūn</i> as the origin. This surname is also found in Scotland and Ireland.","History: A Scottish family of this name derives it from lands at Middleto(u)n near Kincardine. The Scottish physician Peter Middleton practiced in New York City after 1752 and was one of the founders of the medical school at King's College (now Columbia University) in 1767. One of the earliest of the Charleston, SC, Middleton family of prominent legislators was Arthur Middleton, born in Charleston in 1681. The name has also been established in Ireland since at least the 13th century; its presence was reinforced by settlers in the 17th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Midthun","meanings":["Norwegian: habitational name from any of about ten farmsteads in western Norway named Midtun, from Old Norse <i>mith</i> ‘middle’ + <i>tún</i> ‘enclosure, farmstead’. Compare   Middleton  ."]},{"name":"Melton","meanings":["English (northern): habitational name from any of various places, for example in Leicestershire, Lincolnshire, Norfolk, and Yorkshire, all of which have the same origin as   Middleton  , with Old English <i>middel</i> replaced by its Old Norse equivalent <i>methal</i> after the Scandinavian settlement of northern and eastern England."]},{"name":"Middlebrook","meanings":["English: habitational name from a lost <i>Micklebrook</i> in Blackburn (Lancashire), recorded as <i>Mikelbroc</i> in the 13th century. The placename appears to derive from Old English <i>micel</i> ‘big’ + <i>brōc</i> ‘brook, stream’. The surname has undergone a dissimilatory or folk-etymological change from <i>Mickle-</i> to <i>Middle-</i>."]},{"name":"Milton","meanings":["English and Scottish: habitational name from one or other of the many places called Milton, or sometimes Middleton (see   Middleton  ) and occasionally Melton (see   Melton  ), most of which derive from Old English <i>middel</i> ‘middle’ or <i>myln</i> ‘mill’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’."]}]},{"name":"Sir","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From Old Norse, originally a byname meaning ‘bride, wife’; in mythology the name of Thor's golden-haired wife."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Robert de Middelton was born about 1215, in Middleton, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Hugh de Middleton, was 21 and his mother, Mrs- Hugh de Middleton, was 17. He had at least 3 sons with Hugonis."},"et":{"Abt 1215–":"umbes 1215–Surnud","1215–Male":"1215–Surnud","1222–Female":"1222–Surnud","1220–Female":"1220–Surnud","1244–1285":"1244–1285","1250–1297":"1250–1297","1250–Male":"1250–Surnud","1196–Male":"1196–Surnud","1200–Female":"1200–Surnud","1215":"1215","1200":"1200","1244":"1244","1222":"1222","1297":"1297","1220":"1220","Abt 1215":"umbes 1215","1285":"1285","1196":"1196","1250":"1250","Abt 1219":"umbes 1219","abt 1244":"umbes 1244","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Midelton, Yorks, England":"Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Middleton, West Riding Yorkshire, England":"Middleton, Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Stockeld, Yorkshire, England":"Stockeld, Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"Abt 1215–":"noin 1215–Kuollut","1215–Male":"1215–Kuollut","1222–Female":"1222–Kuollut","1220–Female":"1220–Kuollut","1244–1285":"1244–1285","1250–1297":"1250–1297","1250–Male":"1250–Kuollut","1196–Male":"1196–Kuollut","1200–Female":"1200–Kuollut","1215":"1215","1200":"1200","1244":"1244","1222":"1222","1297":"1297","1220":"1220","Abt 1215":"noin 1215","1285":"1285","1196":"1196","1250":"1250","Abt 1219":"noin 1219","abt 1244":"noin 1244","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Midelton, Yorks, England":"Yorkshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Middleton, West Riding Yorkshire, England":"Middleton, Yorkshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Stockeld, Yorkshire, England":"Stockeld, Yorkshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"Abt 1215–":"environ 1215–Décédé","1215–Male":"1215–Décédé","1222–Female":"1222–Décédée","1220–Female":"1220–Décédée","1244–1285":"1244–1285","1250–1297":"1250–1297","1250–Male":"1250–Décédé","1196–Male":"1196–Décédé","1200–Female":"1200–Décédée","1215":"1215","1200":"1200","1244":"1244","1222":"1222","1297":"1297","1220":"1220","Abt 1215":"environ